textAnnotations.description:
The labourous job of flail threshing
was not successfully mechanised
until 1786 when Andrew Meikle
a scottish millwright invented a machine
with a revolving drum in a concave housing.
The principle has since been improved
but never superseded and is basically
the same in a modern combine harvester.
The use of threshing machines spread
quickly and during the early part of the
19t century mobs of farm labourers
broke them up fearing job losses
as flail threshing had been a regular
source of winter employmentfor journeymen
farm labourers.
